# 🎯 RAILS CODE QUALITY & OPTIMIZATION RULES

## Summary

All code written for this project must be fully optimized for Rails, following idiomatic Ruby and Rails conventions, maximizing performance, maintainability, and security. Code must be production-ready, DRY, and free of placeholders or incomplete sections. All solutions should be evaluated using the reward/penalty framework below.

---

## 📋 RAILS CODE QUALITY & OPTIMIZATION REQUIREMENTS

### 🔧 General Principles

* Adhere strictly to Rails conventions (naming, file structure, RESTful controllers, etc.)
* Write idiomatic Ruby: prefer expressive, concise, and readable code
* Use Rails' built-in features (ActiveRecord, scopes, validations, callbacks, etc.) before reaching for custom code
* Avoid technical debt: no speculative features, no unused code, no TODOs or placeholders
* All code must be production-ready and maintainable

### ⚡ Performance & Efficiency

* Optimize ActiveRecord queries: use eager loading (`includes`), select only needed columns, and avoid N+1 queries
* Use database indexes and constraints where appropriate
* Prefer batch operations and database-level logic for large data sets
* Use background jobs (ActiveJob) for slow or non-blocking tasks
* Avoid unnecessary memory allocations and object instantiations
* Use caching (fragment, Russian doll, low-level) where it provides real benefit

### 🔄 Parallelization & Scalability

* Use Rails' built-in concurrency features (e.g., parallel queries, background jobs) where justified by workload
* Leverage database-level parallelism (e.g., bulk inserts/updates) when handling large data sets
* Avoid premature optimization; only parallelize when there is a clear, measured benefit

### 🎨 Style & Idioms

* Follow the Ruby Style Guide and Rails Style Guide (e.g., snake_case, two-space indentation, no semicolons)
* Use meaningful, descriptive names for variables, methods, and classes
* Keep controllers skinny and models fat; extract service objects or concerns for complex logic
* Use partials and view components for reusable UI
* Write concise, intention-revealing comments only where the code's purpose is not obvious

### 🛡️ Error Handling & Edge Cases

* Validate all user input at both the model and controller level
* Handle exceptions gracefully; never expose stack traces or sensitive info to users
* Use strong parameters in controllers
* Handle nils and empty collections safely and idiomatically

### 🔒 Security

* Use Rails' built-in security features: CSRF protection, strong parameters, encrypted credentials, etc.
* Never trust user input; always sanitize and validate
* Avoid SQL injection, XSS, and mass-assignment vulnerabilities

### 🌐 Portability & Compatibility

* Ensure code runs on all supported platforms (macOS, Linux, etc.)
* Avoid OS-specific calls unless absolutely necessary, and provide alternatives or clear documentation

### 🚀 Modern Practices

* Use current, supported Rails and Ruby versions
* Prefer modern, efficient libraries and gems; avoid deprecated or unmaintained dependencies
* Use Hotwire/Turbo and Tailwind in line with Rails best practices

